{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "intro",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Step 8: Web UI hello world\n",
    "\n",
    "![Step 8 diagram](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jaewilson07/bird-watcher/main/docs/diagrams/08-step.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "## What you're building today\n",
    "\n",
    "A webpage that says \"bird watcher\".\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll use **FastAPI** — a Python web framework. It takes a few lines to spin up a server that responds to browser requests.\n",
    "\n",
    "By the end of this notebook you'll have a real local web server responding with an HTML page. Browse to it and you see your first bird watcher UI.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Note about Colab\n",
    "\n",
    "Colab's free tier doesn't expose ports to the internet, so we'll mostly simulate what the server looks like. The same code works on your laptop — just run it and visit `localhost:8000`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "what-is-web-framework",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 8.1 — What is a web framework?\n",
    "\n",
    "When you visit `https://google.com`, your browser sends an HTTP request to Google's servers. Something on the other end reads the request, decides what to send back, and returns HTML.\n",
    "\n",
    "**FastAPI** is a Python library that handles the boring parts (parsing requests, formatting responses, error handling) so you just write \"when someone visits /, send them this HTML\".\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "@app.get(\"/\")\n",
    "def home():\n",
    "    return \"<h1>bird watcher</h1>\"\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "That's literally a whole web page."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "install",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "!pip install -q fastapi uvicorn[standard]\n",
    "print(\"OK\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "app",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 8.2 — Write the app\n",
    "\n",
    "Two routes: `/` shows the title. `/health` returns JSON (a common pattern for checking a service is alive)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "app-code",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from fastapi import FastAPI\n",
    "\n",
    "app = FastAPI(title=\"Bird Watcher\")\n",
    "\n",
    "INDEX_HTML = \"\"\"\n",
    "<!doctype html>\n",
    "<html>\n",
    "<head><title>Bird Watcher</title></head>\n",
    "<body style=\"font-family: sans-serif; max-width: 600px; margin: 4em auto;\">\n",
    "  <h1>bird watcher</h1>\n",
    "  <p>Watching the feeder. Telling you what's there.</p>\n",
    "  <p><a href=\"/gallery\">Browse the gallery</a> (will exist after issue #9)</p>\n",
    "</body>\n",
    "</html>\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "@app.get(\"/\")\n",
    "def home():\n",
    "    return INDEX_HTML\n",
    "\n",
    "@app.get(\"/health\")\n",
    "def health():\n",
    "    return {\"status\": \"ok\"}\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"App defined with 2 routes:\")\n",
    "for route in app.routes:\n",
    "    if hasattr(route, \"path\"):\n",
    "        print(f\"  {route.methods} {route.path}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "test-client",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 8.3 — Test the routes\n",
    "\n",
    "FastAPI includes a TestClient so we can hit the routes without spinning up a real server."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "test-client-code",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from fastapi.testclient import TestClient\n",
    "\n",
    "client = TestClient(app)\n",
    "\n",
    "r = client.get(\"/\")\n",
    "print(f\"GET /  ->  {r.status_code}\")\n",
    "print(r.text[:200])\n",
    "\n",
    "r = client.get(\"/health\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nGET /health  ->  {r.status_code}\")\n",
    "print(r.json())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "run-server",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 8.4 — Run it for real (on your laptop)\n",
    "\n",
    "If you're in Colab, you can skip this step — the TestClient already proved the routes work.\n",
    "\n",
    "On your laptop, save this app to `src/bird_watcher/web.py` and run:\n",
    "\n",
    "```bash\n",
    "uvicorn bird_watcher.web:app --reload\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Then open http://localhost:8000 in your browser. You should see \"bird watcher\"."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "save-app",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Save the app to a real file so it can be reused in issue #9\n",
    "from pathlib import Path\n",
    "Path(\"src/bird_watcher/web.py\").parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n",
    "Path(\"src/bird_watcher/web.py\").write_text(\n",
    "    '\"\"\"Web UI for the bird watcher.\"\"\"\\n'\n",
    "    'from fastapi import FastAPI\\n\\n'\n",
    "    'app = FastAPI(title=\"Bird Watcher\")\\n\\n'\n",
    f'INDEX_HTML = {INDEX_HTML!r}\\n\\n'\n",
    "    '@app.get(\"/\")\\n'\n",
    "    'def home():\\n'\n",
    "    '    return INDEX_HTML\\n\\n'\n",
    "    '@app.get(\"/health\")\\n'\n",
    "    'def health():\\n'\n",
    "    '    return {\"status\": \"ok\"}\\n'\n",
    ")\n",
    "print(f\"Saved: src/bird_watcher/web.py ({Path('src/bird_watcher/web.py').stat().st_size} bytes)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "wrap-up",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Done?\n",
    "\n",
    "If `GET /` returned your HTML and `GET /health` returned `{\"status\": \"ok\"}`, the web server is wired up. 🎉\n",
    "\n",
    "## What's next\n",
    "\n",
    "Issue **#9: Web UI gallery**. Hello world is fine, but birds are prettier than text. Next we add a `/gallery` route that lists every sighting with a thumbnail. 🐦"
   ]
  }
